<Review>I received an email from Shleppers with links to their reviews and decided I would add my story. It seems like they get lots of great feedback from most everyone, but I did see a few bad ones so I‚Äôm sharing my experience also so that customers know what to expect.

My husband and decided to move to TX because life here just got too expensive. My husband works in sales so he was fortunate enough to relocate and keep his job. My job was to figure out where we were going to go and how to get there.

I‚Äôll save you the details on finding a house! But to find movers, I did what I always do and went online to find a company that could handle interstate moving. Shleppers was a funny name but they appeared to be a serious business nonetheless with lots of locations and many years in business. It made me feel confident I wasn‚Äôt contacting some fly by night crooks, and that was very important to me.

I spoke with one of their reps on the phone, and after speaking with me for a few minute about my needs, it was clear that I needed a lot of help. We have three kids, tons of stuff, and going through all the details on the phone seemed a bit much for me. So, the rep signed me up for a ‚Äòvirtual estimate‚Äô. A woman from Shleppers contacted me on my iphone and toured through my house with me. She was very thorough, making sure that I opened my closets and drawers so that she could gauge how many boxes were needed. We looked at the stairs, the driveway, the access--basically everything you could think of to make sure that there were no surprises come move day. It took about 30-45 minutes I‚Äôd guess, but I was happy to do it to make sure everything was clear about what we needed. I‚Äôve read horror stories about prices changing, and I wanted to do everything possible to prevent that from happening.

The next day I heard from Bobby. He had reviewed the inventory, the home, the access, and looked up the destination on Google Maps to see if their truck would have access. He also was extremely polite and thorough and did a great job explaining how long distance moves are handled. I had no idea. I thought they would pick up our stuff and drive to TX right away, but evidently that‚Äôs not how it works.

In the end, Bobby helped me to book the move, and on move day, six shleppers showed up wearing masks (the good kind!). Wow. I couldn‚Äôt believe how fast they worked. The idea of doing it myself became even more ridiculous while I watched them work at an incredible pace. I thought the move would take much longer than it did.

Fortunately, there were no surprises and my stuff was picked up and brought back to their warehouse. About three weeks later, which is what we wanted, we got our stuff here in TX. A couple of boxes kinda lost their strength in the trailer, but the contents were fine and all of our furniture arrived safely. One of the movers slightly scratched a door post moving in a huge table, but nothing major. I suppose nothings perfect and we had over 400 items so to me we did well.

We were in touch with their General Manager while the items were in storage and before they hit the road. He was a lovely guy named Jesse. He was police and accommodating. That was my experience with him anyway.

I hope this helps and definitely recommend moving with Shleppers. They are an honest company with their act together.< /Review><Pictures>None<//Pictures>< user>

< Pics>
None</Pics>
< Resp>
{'time': 1597772319134, 'text': "Dear Vanessa. Thank you for allowing us to handle your move.\n\nThe charge to which you are referring is called a shuttle fee, and it is standard charge throughout the moving industry when a tractor trailer, which is used by all moving companies for interstate travel, does not have access to a delivery site, thus requiring off-loading into a smaller truck to make delivery. When there is access, no expense is incurred by us or passed on to our customers. It is a charge that can happen if circumstances dictate as much.\n\nWe do not benefit from this fee at all, because it is a passthrough expense, and in fact it slows us down and is disruptive to our operation. We try to avoid it ourselves.\n\nThere is often no way to know in advance when a shuttle will be required. It could be the slope of the road, the weather conditions, tree branches, tight corners, local regulations, or any number of other factors that prevent large trucks from entering. When we know a shuttle will be needed, we inform customers and build it into the price, and if we don't know, we inform them of the possibility. This is all above board and abundantly honest. So above board that every customer is told this over the phone, and then signs in three different places affirming their understanding before we do the move.\n\nWe understand getting an extra charge is unwanted and can be frustrating. That is why we work hard to be above board about it. All customers booking with us receiving the exact same information, and though there are a few frustrated people each year that take out their frustrations online to whom you refer, there are thousands and thousand of customers each year that incur the same charge that say nothing, because they were told. Those same customers refer us business all the time because of our transparency and service.\n\nWe hope that you are happy in your new home and are available by phone should you need our assistance."}< /Resp>

< review>
Helpful staff and lots of choices of things to paint. I've been here a few times and each time has been great.
Came here last with my 18 month old and the staff was nice to help with getting her set up.
Free 2 hour parking across the street or you can pay a meter.
A little pricey (price of item, price to fire plus a price for each painter), but this isn't a daily or weekly things so it's fine with me.
Great activity for relaxing and for young ones.</review>

<Review>Went out with the significant other for our first SUP experience. Quick and easy tutorial and conditions were great. Would definitely go again. Just make sure to try and do reservations since trying to do a spontaneous walk up appointment is likely not to get you a spot...that's what we tried to do the day before and there were no slots for most of the day haha.

Water was just the right temperature, the channel is extremely calm with the exception of when a boat would come by. If we were to do it again we would consider doing 2 hours just so we could sit and relax for some portion of the time.

May have to try the dog SUP next time =)< /Review>< rate>

<Text>My dog and I loved our lesson with Sam and Jack a few years ago. Now my dog is a paddling pro!

SUP Connection is great for renting because it's so convenient. If I had my own board, I would have to either carry it to the water or blow it up every time I wanted to go out on the water. I know my dog would get antsy waiting and I think carrying everything to and from my car would be more tiring of a workout than paddling for two hours.

It's easy to reserve a board online and then just show up to SUP Connection, leave my car keys and shoes by their tent, and get on the water. All the employees are friendly and helpful and the equipment is always in good condition. Really glad I signed up for their membership for the rest of the season! I plan on having a membership next summer, too.<//Text><resp>None< /resp></record></dataset><record>

<Review>In many of the the British colonized countries a jersey is defined as a knitted garment with long sleeves worn over the upper body.  In America we call this a sweater.  Americans define a jersey as a uniform worn by athletes.
Everyone that I know just called the place Jersey Mike's (leaving off Subs).  This had really confused me I didn't know if the place was going to sell sweaters or athletic uniforms.
In the end I learned a very valuable lesson, don't take thing so literal.  We all need to be able to think outside the box just like this Mike guy who invented Jersey Mike's.  THANK YOU MIKE YOU ARE THE BEST.  Teaching us new lessons every day.</Review>< pics>

< Review>
Great for a night with friends in a fun atmosphere - a little bit overhyped.  I would highly recommend making a reservation ahead of time - this spot is really popular every night of the week.  We were seated outside which was still fun since there were heat lamps and we were a big group.  The tacos were tasty but didn't come with many condiments (guacamole, cholula, salsa). The next time I go back, I'll definitely explore other parts of the menu.  The margaritas were good and strong, but filled with so much ice that it wasn't worth the $9.  Still a fun spot if you're looking to try something new in the Marina.</Review>

<username>Leslie Georgatos< /username><user>107765406144071367509<//user>< text>
This is a place I would do a birthday.

The margaritas (of many flavors) are quite good. It's a loud and fun atmosphere with lots of groups and young people. I always get tacos - they have some interesting ingredients that are out of the norm (the mahi borracho is my favorite). They also have some good seafood starters and if you're hungrier, chilaquiles.

It's the slightly less rowdy, slightly more upscale/authentic sibling to Tacolicious.</text>

Wowza! I love this place. Ate here for dinner and had a couple cocktails. It was dark and romantic. Great, friendly staff and the food... my God, the food. <UserId.>108699185531538212959</UserId.><user_name>Krista Seiden< /user_name><Time>1362518685838<//Time>< Rate>
4<//Rate>
< review>
I've been here a few times now and love it each and every time. Both the carne asada tacos and the crispy chicken tacos are amazing, and the chilaquiles casi listos (nacho like appetizer) was absolutely amazing. Another nice surprise was their sangria. I love sangria, and having a decent amount of it when I lived in Europe tend to be quite picky when it comes to good sangria, but Mamacita gets a thumbs up from me.

The only reason I'd knock them a bit is their service. Its not bad, but when it gets really crowded (as in every weekend night) its not great either and it tends to take a while to get served. But in my opinion, its worth the wait. YUMMMMM</review>

<Time>1623690703798</Time>< review>
i am a on the fence about  recommending to go with AQS. I will say they are awesome at customer service. Their service managers (Elinore who has helped me) is top notch. and the installer (Rene) is great at his job.
Now to my experience and as to why i dont know whether to recommend or not to.
With the initial visit(THE QUOTE): the sales people were really cool and really good at their pitch. The one thing i would say is to make sure you know exactly what you are getting before they leave. i was quoted a price for a Rheem unit. Thinking i was getting a Rheem unit as promised i waited to see what was done after it was all installed.  I noticed they installed a RUUD unit. I called to express my concern and got the whole, RHEEM makes RUUD so its basically the same thing answer. so i feel i got charged for a RHEEM but got a RUUD. (OVERCHARGED)
The installation has not gone as smooth as i thought it was going to be. (maybe i was just the lucky one for all the problems to happen to).  Although all the issues that have came up after the install have been addressed and taken care of in a quick manner.
So overall, the air conditioner is working great and doing what it is supposed to do. All i can say is if you do decide to go with AQS, i just hope you have a better experience than i have had. I dont regret getting the ac unit because we really needed it but i do feel i got had a little bit.<//review>

< Text>
This company was contracted by my home warranty company. All I can say is - RUN!
Everything started off fine with this Company diagnosing the problem. However, once the work needed to be done, there were nothing but problems. My home warranty company called me and told me my uncovered charges out of pocket totaled $900. I asked my home warranty company to provide an itemized estimate of what was being charged to include what the warranty company would be covering. The warranty company stated I had to call the vendor (this shop) and request the information. I  called this company and they told me they were under no obligation to provide anything to me because the warranty company was their client and I was not. Of course, it is unlawful for any Contractor to perform work without entering into a binding agreement with the consumer, which includes detailing the charges in writing.
Finally, after much battling, a manager with the home warranty company contacted their offices and field rep to request this company send me something in writing. I did receive an invoice, which was not itemized and was only for my charges, which stated $900. In a separate conversation, I spoke with Mike at this company who said I could ‚Äúelect‚Äù to pay an additional $1150 for a HERS test, or I could find my own company for half the price. This was new information to me at the time due to not previously being disclosed on the estimate for $900. I still did not have the detailed estimate of all charges - to me and the home warranty company.
Finally, Ariana called me to schedule an appointment to complete the work and, at that time, told me $2,050 was due upon completion. I questioned this because that‚Äôs not what I had been told. I also raised the issue that I STILL hadn‚Äôt received an itemized estimate for all the work being done. She said the $2,050 was for the $900 noncovered charged, and $1150 for a permit! Permit?! This was news to me again! My estimate stated within the $900, the permit was covered! When discussing the estimate, Ariana stated she had no knowledge of what the home warranty  was paying. I asked her how is it possible they don‚Äôt know what charges the home warranty company is covering if they are doing the job. None of it made any sense. She couldn‚Äôt answer my questions, said she would have her manager call me, and after my numerous requests to proceed with scheduling the appointment  while we work through the issues in tandem, she refused.
Mike, the manager, called me the next business day to talk through everything yet he was rude, belligerent, would not listen to a word I was saying while talking over me, and didn‚Äôt tell me anything outside of the HERS test and permit are the same charge. Interesting, as they are two entirely different things and one was optional (HERS test), per Mike, while the other was due and payable upon completion per Ariana (Permit). Mike still would not schedule the appointment, explain why I could not receive all the charges in writing, and animatedly refused as I offered we call the home warranty company together to work through a resolution.
His next call was to the home warranty company wherein which he refused to complete the work.
All-in-all, this company and their employees morals, ethics, and manners are questionable.</Text>

107048846057061267357< /UserId.>
<text>If I could give zero stars, I would. This place has some shady business practices. I will elaborate.

Selling to them is near impossible, or they're just really biased. Not to mention, that the staff are unreasonable and that the staff will think that they happen know better than you do. Unless you happen to be a loyal customer, chances are that they may not always have a bedside manner. Or there might be miscommunication on their part. Not uncommon sure, but it's still a bit difficult when trying to get a second opinion.

Recently, I tried selling them a bunch of consoles to them. I had about six spare consoles. Out of the six that I brought up, they were willing to only buy two of them. Which happened to be a PS2 and a 60GB fat PS3. And the fat PS3 isn't exactly easy to find these days as they appear to be uncommon now. The other four consoles that I would have brought in were an original Xbox, two elite Xbox 360s, and a slim PS3. They completely disregarded the slim PS3, but that was just part of the problem. They simply told me they would not accept original Xbox systems and all Xbox 360 models. As for their reasoning, they simply stated, "These aren't in demand and it would be harder to  resell them and the value just isn't worth it to
us." So basically, you cannot sell Microsoft systems to them for the most part. Probably including the Xbox One, as well. As for the demand part, there are tons of people collecting for the original Xbox. If you look on game collecting communities, you will see people are still buying games for the system and more uncommon limited edition variants of the system. So I never believed that part, either. Second of all, they basically told me to do my business elsewhere by referring me to other buying apps. That isn't necessarily a good thing for a store that wants to be taking in stock. So basically, they're a video game store that is biased and won't buy Microsoft systems. That's my verdict there.

I do recall when I sold a PS2 to them back in 2018. It was a well working system but they wouldn't buy it only because one of the doors to the memory card slots was missing. Which never affected the system at all. I get that it may not look as presentable, but if you were to put a memory card in the slot, you wouldn't notice a difference! Again, they're really picky.

Their prices are insane. I mean, $25 for a Greatest Hits copy of Dark Cloud for the PS2? Not to mention that the case was faded and the fact the game itself is worth a bit over $10. But still, a GREATEST HITS copy. Let that sink in. And they had the nerve to charge $50 for its sequel, which is worth half of that. So, yeah. Totally insane to say the least.

Bottom line, doing business with these people is just completely meaningless. I wouldn't waste my time with them any further. The way they run a business is just demoralizing. You can't let biased opinions get in the way of your business. Especially when your so called observations are completely false! Not sure if this review is going to stop people from shopping here, but still. Just do your business elsewhere and don't give Play n' Trade a second thought.< /text></record>

Overall this place has great game values from any other game store I've come across, but there customer service is poor. < rate>
4</rate>
< text>
Very nice video game store that sells retro, but also new video games, consoles, controller, and pretty much anything you need to be a gamer. Prices might be a little high for some people, but that's what Black Friday is for. Is your video game console broken or damaged? Play N Trade will buy it, or even fix it for you. They also sell other things, such as phones, iPods, and TV streaming boxes.  Word to the wise, however. If you're looking to buy an old console or game, or even ANYTHING old at all, just try looking for garage sales or thrift shops, which just might have that old N64 or Genesis you've been looking for. Then buy it for $10. OKAY, MAYBE THAT MIGHT NOT HAPPEN, but it's always worth a shot. After all, who wants to spend over $100 for a N64, just to play the games? Get a pc with an emulator for crying out loud</text>

<Text>I'm a travel nurse from St louis. And enjoy a variety of food. Of course I had dessert first! Apple cobbler cooked and served hot to perfection with melting ice cream. Crab cake appetizer with salad. Dinner for me was grilled Salmon with shrimp skewers, some veggies and slaw. I do wish my salmon was marinated or a little seasoned. This place is fantastic - food, service, atmosphere!

We went for happy hour, so we ordered potato skins, sliders, Mac n cheese, nachos, and some drinks.  Every item was a decent serving and tasted great.  Their drinks were also good! They don't rip you off on the alcohol.  I also liked that their happy hour menu had many items to choose from.  It's disappointing when there's only 3 items to pick from at other places- not the case here.

I would 100% go again especially because I got to watch the Dodger game! And easy to find street parking.</review>

< Review>
This is a great spot in the Marina to get something to eat. There's a lot of patio dining, and they are exceptionally mindful of covid19 precautions. The food was amazing. They even took a special request for something not on the menu, and didn't charge a fortune for it which was great. The food was very tasty. Our server was Johnny on the spot with whatever we needed. I'd recommend eating here if you're in Marina Del Rey< /Review>

<review>This place is fantastic - food, service, atmosphere!

We went for happy hour, so we ordered potato skins, sliders, Mac n cheese, nachos, and some drinks.  Every item was a decent serving and tasted great.  Their drinks were also good! They don't rip you off on the alcohol.  I also liked that their happy hour menu had many items to choose from.  It's disappointing when there's only 3 items to pick from at other places- not the case here.

I would 100% go again especially because I got to watch the Dodger game! And easy to find street parking.< /review><pics>None< /pics><response>{'time': 1593625154675, 'text': 'Thank you so much for all of your kind words Edna!!! Glad you had great time. See you soon.\nTony P'}< /response>< Gmap_id>

<Text>This place has a great atmosphere, friendly service, and great views if you're in the dining section. My husband went to watch the NBA final game last night, and had a great time. < text>
This place has a great atmosphere, friendly service, and great views if you're in the dining section. My husband went to watch the NBA final game last night, and had a great time. We sat in the bar area, which was buzzing with excited sports fans. We ate during happy hour, and while the appetizers were only $7.95, the food was a bit bland, but we didn't have any entrees, so I couldn't speak for any signature dishes. Overall, it was enjoyable and my husband and son mentioned a few more times today, how much they enjoyed the crowd and staff at Tony P's. Definitely recommend, but maybe try a seafood dish, which I'm sure will be better than the nachos, spinach- artichoke dip, and calamari. The quesadilla was decent and so were the potato skins.</text>

<review>Gave it four stars because the server was not all that good. He came pretty quickly once we sat down but we got our food and asked for some hot sauce and it literally took him about 15-20 min to come back with it. <pics>None</pics><review>We were staying right next to Tony Ps on the Marina. We wanted a good salad (had dinner plans at an all you can eat Brazilian restaurant so wanted something lighter) and saw that this place had some good ratings. It was very busy, apparently the bar is popular for sports games. I ordered a cup of clam chowder and a southern fried chicken salad. I'm a fan of clam chowder, and only order from places that are on the water üôÇ. The chowder was good, but the salad was one of the best salads I've had. Good dressing, chicken was cooked well, had candied pecans, corn and some other stuff in it. Lots of flavor, very good. Service was a little slow, but it was busy.</review>< name>

<user_id>101128729472721895532</user_id><Name>Tokoro B< /Name><Time>1564878940110< /Time><Rating>4</Rating>< text>
An institution in Marina del Rey. Nice outdoor eating space. The menu is pretty typical - steaks, fish, salads, pizza. There is an extensive selection of beers. Service is generally good. Almost everything is garlicky, even when a "no garlic" request is made. The fish is often frozen - ask if you want something fresh and local. (Salmon is farmed, not wild, and comes from either the Pacific Northwest or the Atlantic.) The food is fine, but not spectacular. We eat here often because Grandma loves it, and she can get her bourbon. I like the bouillabaisse and the quinoa and beet salad.< /text>

< text>
Disappointing doesn‚Äôt begin to express the quality of the food here.

The restaurant was deserted (except for the bar) on a Thursday night.  Not a good sign.  My husband ordered the blackened chicken Cajun pasta. What he got was very bland chicken & pasta in a brownish sauce.  No spice, no taste. The chicken was white and had neither been blackened nor subjected to any flavor that could be remotely identified as Cajun.

I ordered the crab cakes. I got bread crumb filler cakes. Crab?  Tasteless.  Like imitation crab.  Maybe they should have called them Krab cakes.  All the food there had the taste and appeal of overprocessed frozen food.  A SmartMeal from the Ralph‚Äôs down the street would have been more enjoyable.

Don‚Äôt bother eating here. Right down the street is an excellent seafood restaurant called Killa Shrimp.  The food there tastes like the entrees were actually caught in the ocean.<//text>

1551468560932< /time>
<Rating>3< /Rating>< Text>
Tony P's is the last of several institutional restaurants that have not evolved beyond the 90s.

Its location to on the water is choice, however it bookends mediocre food and decent service.

Their prices are fairly typical for restaurants along its row with dishes landing between $13 & $24 dollars depending on the dish.

If you are a sports fanatic, the bar area is special. It's Bill for sports enthusiasts and can be a lot of fun depending on the games and energy at the people watching.< /Text>

< rating>
5< /rating>
< review>
As a couple that frequents restaurant's on a very regular basis, I must say that Tony P's really is one of the best all around places to really enjoy. Everything from the parking to the ambiance, the food and most importantly the staff is great. My wife and I have always enjoyed our time at Tony P's. We have been most fortunate to have one of the of the nicest servers on our several recent visits, by the name of Kalie M, who truly adds to our evening. Kalie is so personalbe and truly is concerned that you are having a great meal.  Everything about the place is EASY and friendly. The staff always accommodates us with a smile. If for instance I need a refill or something of that nature, and our server is occupied elsewhere, undoubtedly there is someone at your service. You don't get "it's not my table" attitude.Truly what all restaurants should strive to be. Very well priced offering a very diverse menu. Take the whole family or just a romantic dinner for two over looking the fabulous yachts in the marina. Thank you Tony P's!!<//review>

< text>
The food is mediocre at best- they definitely are relying on their great view of the marina to get people to come in, because it isn‚Äôt the food.
I ordered the fish and chips and added a wedge salad for $4.75. The wedge salad was just lettuce, tomato, and watery blue cheese. When I asked about the onions and the bacon the server said that isn‚Äôt available on the add-on wedge, only the appetizer wedge ($10.95). Nowhere on the menu does it call that out. The flavor really comes from those components mixing with the others. I would recommend skipping the add-on wedge- it was flavorless. It didn‚Äôt even have blue cheese crumbles to help boost the flavor.
Two people at my table ordered the French Onion Soup and they described it as ‚Äúunderwhelming.‚Äù
The fish and chips were decent- not a ton of flavor but tasted fresh, the breading was a little doughy. I substituted the fries for veggies- the veggies were good and you get a large portion (I bet if they scaled down their veggie portion slightly they‚Äôd be able to afford to put some onions and bacon on the wedge salad :) )
Someone at my table had the mahi-mahi and really enjoyed it.
Another person in my party had the salmon- it was cooked nicely but again did not have a lot of flavor.
Our server at the end of the meal explained that an 18% gratuity was added on because ‚ÄúI have to split the tips with my co-workers.‚Äù That really left a bad taste in our mouths because when I said ‚Äúyou have to split it from this table?‚Äù He said ‚Äúyeah we have to tip out.‚Äù I worked as a server through high school and college- tipping out is par for the course. At every restaurant I‚Äôve worked for there is some form of tipping out your back of house, bar, hostess, bussers, etc. It wasn‚Äôt because we were a large group so he had to split the tips with his co-workers, it‚Äôs because that is what you do as a server since they are the ones helping you satisfy your customers.
Two of the people in our party own a boat in the marina and were looking for another restaurant to frequent nearby, but based on last night‚Äôs experience will not be returning to Tony P‚Äôs.<//text>
<Pictures>None</Pictures><response>{'time': 1555364328305, 'text': 'HI Amy, thanks for coming into Tony P\'s. I am sorry about the confusion on the wedge salad. We do offer 2 different wedge salads. One is an add on to an entree (Iceburg wedge, tomatoes, red onions and dressing. $4.75) and one is on the entree salad section (Iceburg wedge, tomatoes, red onions, smoked bacon, crumbled blue cheese and dressing $10.95). We will retrain the salad cook who needs to stir the blue cheese dressing that we make in house, that is full of chunks of blue cheese. I apologize that you didn\'t get that. Regarding the 18% gratuity which is added on to parties of 6 or more. The server didn\'t do a very good job of explaining it to you. Like most restaurants, we add gratuity to tables of 6 or more people. Since you were a server before you understand this policy. Please e-mail me your server\'s name (tony@tonyps.com) and what time you came in. If you do not agree with the added gratuity, please let the manager know and we would take it off.  Our servers "tip out" to the Bussers, Food Runners and Bartenders that help them service your table. They do not share their tips with any other servers. All of this should not have anything to do with you getting great service when you come in. It is all house keeping issues on our side of the restaurant business and I am sorry if you were inconvenienced. Anytime you come into Tony P\'s, and you are not satisfied with service or food please let our managers know. We want everyone to have a great experience.'}< /response>< gmap_id>

As a couple that frequents restaurant's on a very regular basis, I must say that Tony P's really is one of the best all around places to really enjoy. Everything from the parking to the ambiance, the food and most importantly the staff is great. My wife and I have always enjoyed our time at Tony P's. We have been most fortunate to have one of the of the nicest servers on our several recent visits, by the name of Kalie M, who truly adds to our evening. Kalie is so personalbe and truly is concerned that you are having a great meal.  Everything about the place is EASY and friendly. The staff always accommodates us with a smile. If for instance I need a refill or something of that nature, and our server is occupied elsewhere, undoubtedly there is someone at your service. You don't get "it's not my table" attitude.Truly what all restaurants should strive to be. Very well priced offering a very diverse menu. <pictures>None<//pictures>< text>
I've come here many times and always have a great time. The outdoor seating is ideal for datenight as there is a view of the marina (there are heat lamps) and all the boats and the marina are lit up. Great to watch the sunset. It is a beautiful ambiance for either a table for two or the whole family.
There is also a bar with lots of beers on tap and the bartenders make great cocktails too! This place is set up with tons of TVs so that every football game is available to watch during the season, or any sport for that matter. I think I come here for every big sport event; football playoffs, basketball plays, Sunday football brunch, and baseball playoffs.
The food is great. I love getting the cajun penne pasta; great portion size for your money and tastes amazing. The fish and chips are the best I think I've ever had and there is a tuxedo cake desert which is a must every time I go here.
The wait staff is very friendly and I don't think I have ever sat long for any help or service. They are attentive and approachable. I highly recommend this place to anyone who lives in the area (or doesn't) or someone visiting and staying near LAX. Won't be disappointed.< /text>

< text>
I have been coming here for over 15 years! Almost everytime I've been here, the staff is friendly and informed of their menu and selections. Timing to me is important in a restaurant, you don't like to be pushed through and out the door, and this establishment has never done that, actually the opposite there have been several times a group and myself come here and seriously feel like we at grandmas house, relaxing and down to earth environment. Big plus is they have amazing bloody Mary's and they keep a great stock beers (allagash my fav) the food menu is tried and true and they stick to what they're good at. Very refreshing to have this local gem for a good night out to eat. Overall my fav is the surf and turf crab/ or lobster and steak.< /text>
